gation, and aspect). The chapters presented in this volume provide case studies from several, typologically unrelated languages. Apart from novel analyses of new as well as well-known facts, the contributions also provide interesting aspects of and challenges for Phase Theory in general, by critically exploring a number of theoretical extensions, proposing new syntactic mechanisms, and sharpening our tools for linguistic analysis.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGenerative grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 0aMinimalist theory (Linguistics). 4aGenerative Syntax. 4aPhase. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMinimalist Program.  aSyntax.1 aGehrke, Berit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrillo, Nino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrohmann, Kleanthes K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrohmann, Kleanthes K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKamiya, Masaaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDonald, Jonathan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManzini, M. Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFadden, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Gereon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrtega-Santos, Iván, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSigurðsson, Halldór Ármann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiland, Bartosz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlis